=80=9Chero of the year=E2=80=9D in 2022, the year of the Top Gun: Maverick =
bonanza: It=E2=80=99s the money.

He=E2=80=99s got as much as it takes. Yes, so do the usual suspects of tech=
 companies and P.E. firms, but Ellison has the money and the extreme motiva=
tion. That=E2=80=99s the first thing you realize when you meet with him. Wh=
ether it=E2=80=99s the insecurity of the only son of a self-made billionair=
e, or simply a personal obsession with the entertainment business, Ellison=
=E2=80=94by design, of course=E2=80=94comes across as the furthest thing fr=
om a vanity producer. This is a guy who was willing to lose his shirt on a =
Terminator movie=E2=80=A6 and
then make another Terminator movie! He watched as his sister Megan became t=
he queen of indie film, turning her house in the hills into an Algonquin fo=
r the Erewhon crowd and breaking an Oscars record with two best picture nom=
inations in the same year=E2=80=94just before her spectacular financial fla=
meout. David kept building, spending family money and bringing in investors=
 like RedBird and KKR and Tencent, biding time until an opportunity like Pa=
ramount presented itself.

=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m overjoyed by this,=E2=80=9D Sherry Lansing, the pionee=
ring former Paramount studio head and producer, told me this afternoon, ref=
lecting what I think is the sentiment around town. Yes, creative people nat=
urally salivate around rich guys willing to spend on art. But it=E2=80=99s =
more than that. =E2=80=9CThe loss of another legacy studio would have been =
tragic,=E2=80=9D Sherry said. =E2=80=9CI think David works hard and loves m=
aking good movies. He=E2=80=99d rather be in an editing room than with the =
bankers.
Failure is not an option to him. He will keep going, and he will have the r=
esources to keep going. It=E2=80=99s a fantastic outcome.=E2=80=9D

Time will tell whether it=E2=80=99s a smart outcome, and likely litigation =
