=E2=80=9D In our chat, Ellison was very quick to deploy tech analogies, esp=
ecially when I expressed skepticism. =E2=80=9CI remember when people said s=
imilar things about Oracle,=E2=80=9D he said, reminding me that he worked t=
here briefly. =E2=80=9CI remember the stories that Oracle was a dinosaur. I=
 remember the stories that Oracle =E2=80=A6 could never manage the cloud an=
d SaaS revolution. And today it=E2=80=99s trading at all-time highs.=E2=80=
=9D

He wasn=E2=80=99t done. =E2=80=9CWhen you think about what Next was when it=
 went into Apple=E2=80=A6 what Pixar was when it went into Disney=E2=80=A6 =
you can take the pure-play content engine that we=E2=80=99ve built at Skyda=
nce, plug that into Paramount, and the already very significantly talented =
leadership team and artists that are working there, and really rejuvenate a=
nd reinvigorate the
company,=E2=80=9D he said. Yes, Skydance is the Steve Jobs company in this =
analogy, so take that for what it=E2=80=99s worth.

4. Movies in theaters still matter: Top theater-owner lobbyist Michael O=E2=
=80=99Leary said today he=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cencouraged=E2=80=9D by Skydanc=
e=E2=80=99s history with franchises like Mission: Impossible and Terminator=
=2E When I asked Ellison bluntly whe=
ther he=E2=80=99s planning to increase or=
 decrease the Paramount theatrical output, he said, =E2=80=9CYes, we will a=
bsolutely make more movies [for] theaters.=E2=80=9D But, I pointed out, mos=
t of the Skydance non-franchise movies recently, like Ghosted and Luck for =
Apple, and The Adam Project and Heart of Stone for Netflix, have been made =
for streamers. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s definitely true,=E2=80=9D he said. =
=E2=80=9CI would say Covid factored into a significant amount of that. I do=
n=E2=80=99t believe in a one-size-fits-all approach. It=E2=80=99s always a =
case-by-case decision on, =E2=80=98What is the best decision for
this movie with this filmmaker and this story in this particular moment in =
time?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D So=E2=80=A6 more movies in theaters, unless it does=
n=E2=80=99t make sense to put them in theaters.

5. Finally, this isn=E2=80=99t a flip: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m definitively in=
 this for the long term,=E2=80=9D Ellison told me. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re 1=
5 years into Skydance and, very simply, this is what I wanna do for the res=
t of my life.=E2=80=9D

So here we are. Honestly, I=E2=80=99m not going to crap on Shari. The Redst=
ones had a nice run. In 2000, Viacom was worth about $70 billion and Sumner=
 was the king of content. It was a long, slow, and much-chronicled descent.=
 Yes, Shari took over twin companies together worth $30 billion and orchest=
rated a flawed strategy and an epic period of overall value destruction.

And yet, she had the good sense to recognize what is, in my view, an ideal =
buyer for the family company. Ideal for her, sure, because Ellison is takin=
g on National
Amusements in a deal that values it well above what a company with a 10 per=
cent economic interest in an $8 billion company=E2=80=94plus some movie the=
aters=E2=80=94should expect. Whether the aggrieved B shareholders realize i=
t now or not, Ellison and his deep well of family money will almost certain=
ly be better for this company and its shareholders in the long run. Money w=
ins, and for now, as the age of media moguls has transitioned to the era of=
 the tech mogul, the Ellison money is probably the best an old Hollywood st=
udio could hope for.

